      "interactionPrompt": "Read the text of the Treaty. What did the British promise?",
      "tabs": {
        "primary": {
          "body": "## **THE MAP OF MI'KMA'KI**\n\nLook at the map on the left. In 1752, Nova Scotia didn't really exist yet. The British were just staying in Halifax. The rest of the land was **Mi'kma'ki**.\n\n**THE DEAL:**\nThe British were desperate for peace. To stop the war, they signed a Treaty. They promised to build a **\"Truckhouse\"** (a store) where the Mi'kmaq could trade their goods.\n\n**THE ARGUMENT:**\nLeo says this promise is still alive. He says, \"You promised us a place to trade. You can't take that away just because 200 years have passed.\"\n\nThe Province says the Truckhouse system ended in the 1700s. They think it's ancient history. Leo thinks it's the law.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/truckhouse-map.jpg",
          "credit": "Map of 1760 Truckhouse Locations"
        },
        "legal": {
          "body": "## **THE WORDS THAT MATTER**\n\nThis is the actual text of the Treaty of 1752. Lawyers fight over these exact words.\n\n> *\"It is agreed that the said Tribe... shall have free liberty to bring for Sale... Skins, Feathers, Fowl, Fish or **ANY OTHER THING** they shall have to sell...\"*\n\n**THE LOOPHOLE:**\nLook at the bold words: **\"Any other thing.\"**\n\nLeo's lawyer argues: \"It doesn't say 'Any other thing EXCEPT cannabis.' It says ANY other thing.\" \n\nHe claims this phrase gives the Mi'kmaq the right to participate in the modern economy—whether that's selling lobster, timber, or cannabis.",
          "image": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/36/1752_Peace_and_Friendship_Treaty.jpg",
          "credit": "Original 1752 Treaty Parchment"
        },
        "intel": {
          "body": "## **THE WAMPUM BELT**\n\n**EVIDENCE:** Oral History\n\nThe British wrote their laws on paper. The Mi'kmaq recorded their laws in **Wampum Belts** (beads).\n\n**WHAT IT MEANS:**\nThis belt shows a chain of friendship. It represents a relationship of **Equals**.\n\n**THE ELDER'S VIEW:**\nAn Elder testified: \"We never surrendered. We agreed to share. When you share, you don't tell your partner what they are allowed to do. You respect them. The Province is trying to act like our parent, but the Treaty says we are brothers.\"",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/wampum-ai.jpg",
          "credit": "Wampum Belt Archive"
        }
      }
