      "longTitle": "EXHIBIT C: The 'Musket' Argument",
      "interactionPrompt": "Compare the items. Is cannabis different from a musket?",
      "tabs": {
        "primary": {
          "body": "## **LEO SPEAKS**\n\nLeo Francis takes the stand. He holds an Eagle Feather. He is not nervous.\n\n**HIS ARGUMENT:**\n\"The Crown says cannabis is dangerous. They say they have to ban it to protect people.\n\nBut look at history. In 1760, what did the British trade with us? **Muskets** (Guns). **Gunpowder**. **Rum**.\n\nThose things kill people. But the Treaty protected that trade because we needed those things to survive. If the Treaty allows us to trade Guns, surely it allows us to trade a Plant.\"\n\n**YOUR THOUGHTS:**\nIt's a strong point. Does 'Safety' justify breaking a Treaty if the Treaty originally included weapons?",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/heresleo-AI.jpg",
          "credit": "Leo Francis"
        },
        "legal": {
          "body": "## **SECTION 35: THE PROTECTOR**\n\nLeo relies on **Section 35** of the Constitution. \n\n**WHAT IS IT?**\nSection 35 is the highest law in Canada regarding Indigenous people. It says: \"The existing aboriginal and treaty rights... are hereby recognized and affirmed.\"\n\n**THE 'FULL BOX':**\nLeo argues that his rights are in a 'Full Box.' He has the inherent right to earn a living. The Government can't just take that away.\n\n**THE 'EMPTY BOX':**\nThe Government argues the box is empty until *they* put rights into it. They say Leo only has rights if the Government gives him a license.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/sect35-1-ai.jpg",
          "credit": "Constitution Act, 1982"
        },
        "intel": {
          "body": "## **HISTORY OF TRADE**\n\n**IMAGE:** 18th Century Trade\n\nLook at the picture. The Mi'kmaq and British are trading. \n\n**THE LOGIC:**\n1.  The Treaty guarantees the right to trade for \"Necessaries\" (things you need to live).\n2.  In 1760, \"Necessaries\" included dangerous items like muskets.\n3.  Therefore, just because something is \"dangerous\" doesn't mean it's banned from the Treaty.\n\nLeo is using history to trap the Crown. He is proving that trade has always involved risk.",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/1750-tradingpost.jpg",
          "credit": "Trading Muskets in 1760"
        }
      }
